    "md_faq": {
      "type": "nuracom-faq",
      "blocks": {
        "fq_1": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "question": "How much time will mum actually save?",
            "answer": "<p>Real talk — about <strong>4 to 6 hours per week</strong>. No more checking the forecast before every wash. No more rearranging her day around drying windows. No more rewashing a load that got rained on. No more lugging baskets out and back in.</p><p>Most mums tell us they get a full Sunday afternoon back within the first month — and stop thinking about laundry as a 'task' altogether. It just happens in the background while life keeps going.</p>",
            "open_by_default": true
          }
        },
        "fq_2": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "question": "How much money will it actually save us on power?",
            "answer": "<p>For an average Aussie family of 4, the maths is hard to argue with:</p><ul><li><strong>Tumble dryer</strong> at $1.42/load × 6 loads/week × 52 weeks = <strong>$443/year</strong></li><li><strong>Nuracom Aero</strong> at $0.57/cycle × ~3 cycles/week (bigger capacity = fewer cycles) = <strong>$89/year</strong></li><li><strong>Net saving: $354/year</strong> on energy alone</li></ul><p>Over 5 years that's <strong>~$1,770 in your pocket</strong> — more than the unit cost itself. Show this to your husband. He'll do the maths and approve faster than you can say 'Mother's Day.'</p>",
            "open_by_default": false
          }
        },
        "fq_3": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Our laundry is tiny — will it actually fit?",
            "answer": "<p>That's exactly who Nuracom was built for. It mounts to the <strong>ceiling</strong>, not the floor. When not in use, it sits flush against the ceiling — looks like a clean light fitting. <strong>Zero floor footprint.</strong></p><p>The smaller your laundry, the more useful Nuracom is. No more clothes horse blocking the hallway. No more basket living on the kitchen bench. No more chair drying that one delicate jumper. Everything goes up, dries, comes down — and the floor stays usable.</p>",
            "open_by_default": false
          }
        },
        "fq_4": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Can my husband install it himself?",
            "answer": "<p><strong>If he's ever put up a curtain rod or a shelf, yes.</strong> The mounting kit is included. Step-by-step printed instructions and a video walkthrough come with every unit.</p><p>Most installs take <strong>25–40 minutes</strong> for a first-timer. The unit clicks into the ceiling brackets and the obstruction-sensing system auto-calibrates the moment it's powered on. He'll feel like a hero. You'll have your laundry sorted. Win-win.</p><p>If he's genuinely not handy — see the next question.</p>",
            "open_by_default": false
          }
        },
        "fq_5": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "question": "We don't have a ceiling power point. Is that a deal-breaker?",
            "answer": "<p><strong>Not at all.</strong> A licensed electrician adds a ceiling power outlet in about <strong>20–30 minutes</strong>. Standard work — no permits needed for a homeowner, no gyprock cutting in most cases.</p><p>Average cost in Australia: <strong>$150–$300</strong> depending on state and ceiling type. Get 2–3 quotes — most local sparkies will do it as a quick call-out.</p><p><strong>Important context:</strong> this is a <em>one-time cost</em>. After that, you have a lifetime of better laundry — and you're saving ~$30/week in dryer energy. The electrician fee pays for itself in <strong>5–10 weeks of avoided dryer use</strong>. Then you save forever.</p><p>Many homes already have a ceiling rose from a previous light fitting that the electrician can convert. If yours does, the install is even faster and cheaper.</p>",
            "open_by_default": false
          }
        },
        "fq_6": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "question": "How simple is the electrician part really?",
            "answer": "<p>Genuinely simple. Most sparkies treat it as a <strong>30-minute job</strong>:</p><ul><li>They locate your existing ceiling rose (or nearest power source)</li><li>Tap into the existing wiring</li><li>Install a new ceiling outlet</li><li>Done</li></ul><p>No rewiring, no major gyprock work, no permits required for a standard residential install. We can email you a one-page brief to give your electrician so they know exactly what's needed — saves the back-and-forth.</p><p>Tip: when getting quotes, mention it's a 'ceiling outlet for a 800W appliance' so they can quote accurately. Most will say yes for $150–$250.</p>",
            "open_by_default": false
          }
        },
        "fq_7": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "question": "I'm gifting this and don't know if mum has the right setup. What do I do?",
            "answer": "<p>We've got you. Order it, then <strong>email our installation team a photo of mum's laundry ceiling</strong> (or get her to send one). We'll tell you within 24 hours whether she needs an electrician or just a regular plug.</p><p>If she does need an electrician, we'll give you a list of recommended sparkies in her area and a rough cost estimate. Or you can include it in the gift — pre-pay the install, hand her the unit + a service appointment. Now <em>that's</em> a complete Mother's Day gift.</p>",
            "open_by_default": false
          }
        },
        "fq_8": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Will mum need to lift heavy wet washing to the ceiling?",
            "answer": "<p><strong>Never.</strong> The whole point of Nuracom is that <em>she doesn't lift anything heavy ever again</em>.</p><p>The empty rack lowers to a comfortable hip-height. She hangs clothes at that height (the same height as a clothesline). When she's done, she presses one button and the loaded rack lifts itself up to the ceiling — handling up to <strong>35–45kg</strong> depending on the model.</p><p>If mum has a sore back, dodgy shoulder, or any kind of joint issue from years of laundry-lifting, this is the single biggest physical relief Nuracom delivers.</p>",
            "open_by_default": false
          }
        },
        "fq_9": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "question": "What about energy bills and running cost?",
            "answer": "<p>Each cycle costs about <strong>57¢ to 64¢</strong> depending on the model — based on Australia's current average residential electricity rate of $0.3557/kWh. That's roughly <strong>a third of what a tumble dryer charges</strong> per load.</p><p>For a typical family of 4, expect:</p><ul><li>~$89/year in Nuracom running costs</li><li>vs ~$443/year on a tumble dryer</li><li>= <strong>$354/year back in your pocket</strong></li></ul><p>Plus you stop replacing dryer-shrunk clothes — most families estimate another $200–$400/year saved on wardrobe replacement.</p>",
            "open_by_default": false
          }
        },
        "fq_10": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Will it work in our home? (apartment, rental, weird ceiling)",
            "answer": "<p>Compatible with <strong>standard plasterboard, timber, and concrete ceilings</strong> — that's the vast majority of Australian homes, including most apartments and townhouses.</p><p><strong>Renting?</strong> Two paths:</p><ul><li>Get written landlord/strata consent (many approve because it adds value and replaces a light fitting — easy to revert)</li><li>Some renters install just the ceiling-mount kit and pop the unit off when they move. Message support after purchase and we'll send a 'renter's install guide.'</li></ul><p>If your ceiling is unusual (very high, very low, slanted, exposed beam), send us a photo before ordering and we'll confirm fit.</p>",
            "open_by_default": false
